## Can White People Experience Racism?

### Individual Prejudice vs. Systemic Racism

White people can and do experience **racial prejudice**â€”negative stereotypes, discrimination, and bias based on their race. However, these experiences lack the systemic power component that defines racism in its full sociological sense ([Kinouani, 2020](https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/09/can-white-people-experience-racism-12323491/); [Cole, 2020](https://www.thoughtco.com/racism-vs-prejudice-3026086)).

For example, a white person may face discrimination or harassment due to their race, but this does not translate into systemic barriers that affect their overall social, economic, or political status. In contrast, people of color face both individual acts of prejudice and systemic racism that affect their life trajectories.

### The Myth of Reverse Racism

The concept of "reverse racism" posits that white people can be victims of racism perpetrated by people of color. However, most race scholars and social justice experts regard reverse racism as a **myth** because it ignores the structural power imbalance ([Morris, 2020](https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/09/can-white-people-experience-racism-12323491/); [Nida & Lyman, 2020](https://www.today.com/news/what-does-reverse-racism-mean-it-actually-real-experts-weigh-t185108)).

For instance, affirmative action policies designed to address historical inequalities are sometimes cited as examples of reverse racism. Yet, these policies aim to level the playing field rather than disadvantage white people ([Schievelbein, 2020](https://mndaily.com/246003/opinion/editorial-can-white-people-experience-racism-pt-ii/)).

### Table 2: Comparison of Racism and Reverse Racism Claims

| Criteria                        | Racism Against People of Color                  | Claims of Reverse Racism Against White People      |
|--------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|
| Systemic Power                 | Present and institutionalized                   | Absent or minimal                                   |
| Historical Context             | Centuries of oppression and exclusion           | No comparable history of systemic oppression       |
| Impact on Access to Resources  | Significant and measurable disparities          | No systemic denial of access                        |
| Legal and Institutional Support| Often codified or tacitly supported              | No legal or institutional backing                   |
| Scholarly Consensus            | Recognized as systemic and pervasive             | Generally rejected as a valid concept               |

