## Empirical Evidence and Social Implications

### Structural Racism and Its Effects

Research shows persistent racial disparities in multiple domains:

- **Education:** People of color often attend underfunded schools and face barriers to higher education ([Sensoy & DiAngelo, 2012](https://www.tcpress.com/is-everyone-really-equal-9780807758210)).
- **Criminal Justice:** Disproportionate policing and incarceration rates among Black and Latino populations ([Alexander, 2010](https://newjimcrow.com/)).
- **Housing:** Practices like redlining have historically segregated communities and limited wealth accumulation for minorities ([Mapping Inequality, 1930s](https://dsl.richmond.edu/panorama/redlining/)).
- **Healthcare:** Ethnic minorities experience disparities in access and outcomes ([Williams & Mohammed, 2013](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3863696/)).

These systemic barriers are not experienced by white people to the same extent, highlighting the power imbalance central to racism.

### White Privilege and Complicity

White privilege refers to the unearned advantages white people receive in society due to systemic racism ([Kendall, 2012](https://www.amazon.com/Understanding-White-Privilege-Frances-Kendall/dp/1594513096)). This privilege manifests as:

- Greater likelihood of being treated as individuals rather than representatives of a racial group.
- Less likelihood of being racially profiled or stopped by law enforcement.
- Easier access to economic and social opportunities.

Acknowledging white privilege does not deny individual struggles but contextualizes them within a broader system of racial inequality ([DiAngelo, 2018](https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/317623/white-fragility-by-robin-diangelo/)).

